# Next.js performance & routing

Read `node_modules/next/dist/docs/` before changing routing, data fetching, or layout behavior (this project uses a non-standard Next.js version).

## Client navigation (required)

- Internal links: **`next/link`** with `prefetch`, never raw `<a href="/dashboard/...">`.
- Shared chrome (sidebar, header): **one `layout.tsx`**, not re-wrapped per page.
- Add route-level **`loading.tsx`** for perceived speed on slow segments.

## Server vs client

- **Default to Server Components** — no `"use client"` unless the file needs hooks, browser APIs, or event handlers.
- Push `"use client"` **down the tree** (leaf components), not up to pages/layouts.
- Heavy client-only libs (charts, editors, mermaid): **`next/dynamic`** with `{ ssr: false }` or load inside a small client leaf.

## Data & rendering

- Avoid `export const dynamic = "force-dynamic"` unless auth or uncacheable data truly requires it.
- Fetch in the **closest Server Component**; pass serializable props to client children.
- Prefer **parallel fetches** (`Promise.all`) over sequential awaits in pages.

## File shape = bundle shape

- Large components bloat client JS — enforce the **100-line component limit** (see `component-size-limits` rule).
- Colocate route config (breadcrumbs, nav metadata) in `src/lib/`, not inside page files.
- Do not import server-only modules into `"use client"` files.

## Anti-patterns

```tsx
// ❌ Full reload navigation
<a href="/dashboard/blueprints">Blueprints</a>

// ✅ Client transition
<Link href="/dashboard/blueprints" prefetch>Blueprints</Link>
```

```tsx
// ❌ Page remounts entire dashboard shell
export default function Page() {
  return <DashboardShell><Content /></DashboardShell>
}

// ✅ Shell in app/dashboard/layout.tsx; page renders content only
export default function Page() {
  return <Content />
}
```
